<!-- ASSERTIVENESS -->
<section class="narr" id="s3b" style="background:linear-gradient(180deg,#080808,#08100d);min-height:100vh">
  <div class="ni">
    <div class="ch rv">What could have been different</div>
    <h2 class="nh rv d1">Jake didn't have<br>the words.</h2>
    <div class="nb rv d2">
      <p>When the boys messaged, there was only one answer in Jake's head. He didn't even question it. Going to the pub wasn't a decision — it was just what happened next. The alternative wasn't available to him.</p>
      <p>That's not weakness. That's not a character flaw. It's a skill he was never taught.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="inner-voice rv d2">
      <p>He thought about it later. What would he have even said? "Nah not tonight"? They'd think something was wrong. They'd take the piss. It was easier to just go.</p>
      <p>But was it? He's lying here on a Saturday morning feeling hollow and broke, same as last week. So what was easier, exactly?</p>
    </div>
    <div style="margin:2.2rem 0" class="rv d3">
      <div class="skill-pill o">Skill One — Assertiveness</div>
      <div class="insight" style="margin-top:0.8rem">
        <div class="il o">What it actually is</div>
        <p>Assertiveness isn't aggression, and it's not confidence. It's the ability to say what you need — clearly, calmly, without excessive apology — and let the response be what it is. In rural WA, this skill is almost never taught. It gets read as weakness. It's the opposite.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps rv d3">
      <div class="step" data-n="1"><h4>Decide before the pressure hits</h4><p>Plan it when you're calm: "I'll have two drinks" or "not tonight." Having a position means you're not making the call when the boys are already three in and the pressure is on.</p></div>
      <div class="step" data-n="2"><h4>"I" not "you"</h4><p>"I'm not feeling it tonight" is very different from "you lot drink too much." One is about you. One starts a fight. Real mates will cop the first one.</p></div>
      <div class="step" data-n="3"><h4>You don't owe anyone an explanation</h4><p>"Nah not tonight" is a full sentence. Short, direct, no apology. The more you explain, the more you invite pushback. Say it once, mean it, and let the silence land.</p></div>
      <div class="step" data-n="4"><h4>Offer the alternative</h4><p>"Not the pub tonight but down for a drive tomorrow." You're not rejecting them — just the drinking. That distinction matters, and they'll feel it.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="nb rv d4" style="margin-top:2.2rem"><p>Jake can't go back and use this skill on last Friday. But there'll be another Friday. There always is.</p></div>
